WEBVTT

00:02.626 --> 00:16.822
Well hey everyone, I'm Dave Ripper, lead pastor of Crossway Christian Church here in Southern New Hampshire, where our mission is all about practicing the way of Jesus together as we pursue God, build community and unleash compassion.

00:16.842 --> 00:20.006
Thanks for listening to our Milford Campus sermon podcast.

00:20.527 --> 00:29.677
I pray that what you hear today will help you experience God more deeply and live more and more like Jesus.

00:29.697 --> 00:30.578
Oh, good morning.

00:32.066 --> 00:36.894
For those of you who do not know me, my name is Dan Lyle, I'm one of the pastors here at Crossway.

00:36.914 --> 00:45.387
It's my joy, my honor, my privilege to be with you in this season of this body here in Milford.

00:45.948 --> 00:51.276
And so just thank you for allowing me to share with you and to be with you at this time.

00:52.438 --> 00:56.264
I'm gonna pull a little bit of a Luke Weinrich here for just a moment.

00:57.847 --> 00:59.890
I have a sermon planned and we're gonna get to that.

01:00.290 --> 01:09.605
Yeah, as we were singing together this morning, the Lord brought a passage to mind that I just want to quickly share with you.

01:12.990 --> 01:17.978
As a worship leader, this is probably one of my favorite Psalms.

01:19.500 --> 01:24.789
Psalm 100 says, shout joyfully to the Lord all the earth.

01:26.351 --> 01:28.114
Serve the Lord with gladness.

01:29.026 --> 01:31.949
Come before Him with joyful singing.

01:33.031 --> 01:36.454
Know that the Lord Himself is God.

01:37.536 --> 01:41.400
It is He who has made us and not we ourselves.

01:42.721 --> 01:50.350
We are His people and the sheep of His pasture.

01:51.832 --> 01:57.458
We are His people and the sheep of His pasture.

01:58.370 --> 02:03.877
He is our shepherd, and we are in His care.

02:04.838 --> 02:05.199
Amen?

02:06.821 --> 02:14.230
I remember being a little boy, I grew up in Baptist Church, and I spent my whole life in the Baptist Church until I came here.

02:14.750 --> 02:24.683
But as a little boy growing up in a large traditional Baptist Church, one of the things I remember the most was the sound of the room during Sunday morning worship.

02:26.045 --> 02:27.186
And I remember it because you had

02:27.650 --> 02:31.776
big organ on one side, two pianos on the other side trying to keep up with that big old organ.

02:32.938 --> 02:40.789
And I remember there's times where I would just stand there silently and listen to the congregation sing.

02:41.169 --> 02:48.340
And I think that formed me as even as a little boy in ways that I don't even understand till this day.

02:48.360 --> 02:55.410
And just as we sang that last song I sat in the back row, my head bowed just silently listening to

02:55.970 --> 02:59.595
the sheep of his pasture singing out to him.

03:00.156 --> 03:01.097
So it's a wonderful thing.

03:01.257 --> 03:03.701
So again, I'm honored to be here with you this morning.

03:09.749 --> 03:16.699
So this morning, we're going to talk about something that John invoked during our time of communion.

03:18.101 --> 03:22.066
This morning, we're going to be talking about hope.

03:24.482 --> 03:31.812
And hope is easy to talk about when life is going the way that we expected it to go.

03:33.354 --> 03:43.408
When things are stable, when the future looks reasonably predictable, it's easy to talk about hope in those moments.

03:43.548 --> 03:50.418
But here's the thing, we don't really need much hope when things are good.

03:52.098 --> 03:54.842
We don't really need much hope when things are good.

03:55.423 --> 03:59.930
As Paul reminds us, hope that is seen is not what?

04:01.132 --> 04:01.472
Hope.

04:03.595 --> 04:05.158
Hope that is seen is not hope.

04:05.198 --> 04:08.102
And he gives this to this question.

04:08.142 --> 04:12.449
He says, for who hopes what he already sees?

04:13.350 --> 04:15.533
Who hopes for what he already sees?

04:17.356 --> 04:18.738
G.K. Chesterson

04:18.882 --> 04:27.972
Put it this way, he said, as long as matters are really hopeful, hope is mere flattery or platitude.

04:29.193 --> 04:39.104
It is only when everything is hopeless that hope begins to be a strength at all.

04:40.566 --> 04:48.114
Like all Christian virtues, it is as unreasonable as it is in

04:48.354 --> 04:49.195
dispensable.

04:51.457 --> 05:17.746
When circumstances stretch out longer than we thought they would, when things we trust it begin to shake, when we look around in the path forward, when it feels completely uncertain, those are the moments when hope stops being a nice idea and it becomes something that we desperately, desperately

05:18.050 --> 05:19.773
desperately need.

05:21.555 --> 05:22.837
There's an irony to this.

05:25.160 --> 05:33.573
That when hope is what we need most, it's actually the hardest thing for us to hold on to.

05:36.377 --> 05:41.985
The world we live in right now, it gives us plenty of reason to feel unsettled, right?

05:42.807 --> 05:45.170
Every week seems to bring another headline,

05:45.442 --> 05:52.088
another crisis, another reminder that things are not as secure as we wish they were.

05:52.148 --> 05:57.153
And if we're honest with ourselves, this is not just some sort of existential thing.

05:57.193 --> 06:01.817
Sometimes this is much closer to home.

06:03.959 --> 06:15.250
It shows up in the quiet places of our lives, in the burdens that we carry for our families, in the disappointments that we didn't expect,

06:15.938 --> 06:20.223
in the prayers that seemed to just kind of lingered unanswered.

06:22.585 --> 06:30.855
Hope becomes most necessary precisely when circumstances feel most uncertain.

06:30.915 --> 06:44.850
And that's why Paul concludes his thoughts on hope by saying if we hope for what we do not see with perseverance, we wait eagerly for it.

06:45.762 --> 06:48.646
We wait eagerly for that thing that we hope for.

06:51.109 --> 06:54.333
See, biblical hope is not the same thing as optimism.

06:56.135 --> 07:00.100
It's not pretending that things are better than they actually are.

07:01.742 --> 07:05.167
It's not wishful thinking about the future.

07:07.390 --> 07:08.751
It's none of those things.

07:10.734 --> 07:13.938
Biblical hope is so much deeper than that.

07:15.586 --> 07:21.935
Hope is the settled confidence that God is still at work.

07:23.357 --> 07:24.798
He is still at work.

07:24.859 --> 07:25.980
He is sovereign.

07:26.721 --> 07:29.545
In his providence, he is ruling over us.

07:31.788 --> 07:35.833
Even when we cannot yet see what he is doing, he is still at work.

07:35.853 --> 07:45.106
And sometimes the way God forms that kind of hope in us is through what might look like from the outside

07:46.434 --> 07:51.219
Strange or an reasonable act of faith.

07:53.402 --> 07:58.508
Today we're going to look at one of those moments in the life of the prophet Jeremiah.

08:00.330 --> 08:04.435
The city of Jerusalem is surrounded by its enemies.

08:05.736 --> 08:09.160
The future of God's people looks pretty bleak.

08:10.341 --> 08:14.386
And Jeremiah himself has now been thrown into prison.

08:15.522 --> 08:24.615
And in the middle of that moment, God tells Jeremiah to do something that makes absolutely no sense at all.

08:28.500 --> 08:38.674
As Israel is under siege, God tells Jeremiah to buy a field of all things.

08:41.026 --> 08:42.689
So we can get a sense of the story.

08:42.709 --> 08:50.842
Would you stand with me as we turn to Jeremiah chapter 32 as we read between verses 1 and 15?

08:51.023 --> 09:07.250
The word that came to Jeremiah from the Lord in the 10th year of Zedekiah, the king of Judah, which was the 18th year of Nebuchadnezzar.

09:08.258 --> 09:38.066
Now, at that time, the army of the king of Babylon was besieging Jerusalem, and Jeremiah, the prophet, was shut up in the court of the guard, which was in the house of the king of Judah, because Zedekiah, king of Judah, had shut him up, saying, why do you prophesy, saying, thus says the Lord, behold, I'm about to give this city into the hands of the king of Babylon, and he will take it.

09:38.786 --> 09:48.417
And Zedekiah, King of Judah, will not escape out of the hand of the Caledians, but he will surely be given into the hand of the king of Babylon.

09:49.198 --> 09:54.845
And he will speak with him face to face and see him eye to eye.

09:55.706 --> 09:57.928
And he will take Zedekiah to Babylon.

09:58.609 --> 10:02.754
And he will be there until I visit him to clares the Lord.

10:02.814 --> 10:06.098
If you fight against the Caledians,

10:06.498 --> 10:08.980
you will not succeed.

10:10.862 --> 10:34.444
And Jeremiah said, the word of the Lord came to me saying, Behold, Hannibal, the son of Shalom, your uncle is coming to you saying, but for yourself, by for yourself, my field, which is an anioph, for you have the right of redemption to buy it.

10:35.225 --> 10:36.146
Then Hannibal,

10:36.354 --> 10:55.832
The uncle's son came to me in the court of the of the guard according to the word of the Lord and said to me, by the field that is at Anioth, which is in the land of Benjamin, for you have the right of possession and the redemption is yours.

10:56.473 --> 10:57.794
Buy it for yourself.

10:58.775 --> 11:01.558
Then I knew that this was the word of the Lord.

11:02.899 --> 11:06.002
I bought the field, which was at Anioth from Hemo.

11:06.402 --> 11:12.869
my uncle's son, and I weighed out the silver for him, 17 shekels of silver.

11:13.790 --> 11:21.718
I signed and sealed the deed and called in witnesses and weighed out the silver on the scales.

11:22.699 --> 11:33.010
Then I took the deed of purchase, both of the sealed copy containing the terms and the conditions and the open copy, and I gave the deed of purchase

11:35.042 --> 12:03.474
Baruch, the son of Nira, the son of Mosheah, in the sight of Hamil, my uncle's son, and in the sight of the witnesses who sign the deed of purchase, before all the Jews who were sitting in the court of the guard, and I command at Baruch in their presence, saying, thus says the Lord of hosts, the God of Israel, take these deeds in this sealed deed of purchase,

12:03.650 --> 12:13.001
And in this open deed and put them in earthen jars, an earthen jar that they may last a long time.

12:13.402 --> 12:21.311
For thus says the Lord of hosts, the God of Israel, houses and fields and vineyards will again be bought in this land.

12:21.732 --> 12:22.853
This is the word of the Lord.

12:23.494 --> 12:24.094
Maybe seated.

12:25.716 --> 12:28.480
So I just want to give you a tip.

12:28.560 --> 12:29.481
I went to Bible college.

12:29.561 --> 12:30.482
I went to seminary.

12:31.362 --> 12:39.936
If you're ever sitting in a small group and you have to read from an Old Testament passage and you don't know how to pronounce the names, it truly does not matter what you actually say.

12:39.976 --> 12:42.120
Just say it with confidence.

12:43.142 --> 12:48.430
Just say it with confidence because no one else actually knows how to pronounce it so you're going to be good.

12:51.335 --> 12:57.746
All right, to understand what's happening in this passage, we need to slow down and look carefully at Jeremiah's situation, right?

12:58.210 --> 13:06.942
Because what God asked Jeremiah to do here, it only makes sense when we realize just how bleak things really were.

13:07.783 --> 13:13.030
By this point in Judah's history, Babylon had already conquered the city once.

13:13.771 --> 13:24.566
The Babylonians had removed the rightful king and installed their own ruler over Judah, a puppet king whose very name reflected Babylon's control.

13:25.287 --> 13:27.410
His original name was Mattania,

13:27.938 --> 13:31.564
But the Babylonians changed it to Zedekiah.

13:32.685 --> 13:39.576
Even the king sitting on the throne carried a name given to him by a foreign emperor.

13:40.738 --> 13:43.622
Judah was no longer truly free.

13:45.044 --> 13:49.872
But Zedekiah eventually, he rebelled against Babylon.

13:50.693 --> 13:53.938
And when he did, the Babylonians came back

13:54.146 --> 13:57.951
And now the city of Jerusalem is under siege yet again.

13:57.971 --> 14:01.195
The Babylonian armies have surrounded the city.

14:01.255 --> 14:07.222
The fall of Jerusalem is not some distant possibility anymore and is absolutely imminent.

14:08.304 --> 14:12.088
The outcome is not really in question here.

14:12.429 --> 14:14.171
Jerusalem is about the fall.

14:16.013 --> 14:20.979
And Jeremiah isn't watching all of this from some sort of safe distance.

14:22.141 --> 14:23.122
He's in prison.

14:24.418 --> 14:29.846
King Zedekiah has had him locked up because Jeremiah has been faithfully delivering a message.

14:29.866 --> 14:39.320
The king does not want to hear that Babylon is going to win and that city is going to fall.

14:40.723 --> 14:53.682
So the prophet who is telling the truth about God and what he has said is now sitting in confinement while the city slowly collapses around him.

14:54.690 --> 15:03.904
And it's in this moment that while Jeremiah is sitting there in that prison, that the Lord tells him something very, very specific.

15:05.025 --> 15:07.709
He says, your cousin is going to come to you.

15:08.891 --> 15:11.755
He's going to offer to sell you a field.

15:12.797 --> 15:17.063
And when he does, I want you to buy it.

15:19.627 --> 15:20.789
I want you to buy it.

15:22.892 --> 15:24.274
Think about that for just a moment.

15:25.602 --> 15:27.284
The city is about to fall.

15:29.806 --> 15:33.150
The people are going into exile.

15:35.912 --> 15:40.958
The land itself is about to be overtaken by a foreign army.

15:42.419 --> 15:48.665
And God tells Jeremiah to invest his money in a piece of property just a few miles outside of the city.

15:50.147 --> 15:53.330
A field that at this very, very moment,

15:54.498 --> 15:58.704
Babylonian soldiers may already be marching across.

15:59.926 --> 16:04.493
From any normal perspective, this makes absolutely no sense.

16:05.574 --> 16:06.315
Makes no sense.

16:06.376 --> 16:08.078
It's a terrible investment.

16:09.500 --> 16:15.890
Jeremiah himself may never actually see the land that he is purchasing.

16:17.572 --> 16:19.495
So the obvious question is this.

16:21.278 --> 16:24.242
Why would God ask Jeremiah to do something like this?

16:26.402 --> 16:28.324
Why would he ask him to do something like this?

16:30.146 --> 16:33.129
Moreover, why would Jeremiah actually do it?

16:35.211 --> 16:36.592
Why would he obey the Lord?

16:39.255 --> 16:42.778
Well, because this wasn't really about buying land.

16:44.380 --> 16:45.621
This wasn't about buying land.

16:45.641 --> 16:48.824
This was an act of hope.

16:50.866 --> 16:54.610
This was the act of hope in the face of a bleak situation.

16:57.122 --> 17:00.007
Jeremiah does exactly what the Lord tells him to do.

17:00.047 --> 17:11.086
His cousin shows up just as God said he would, and he offers to sell Jeremiah the field, and Jeremiah buys it.

17:12.929 --> 17:16.676
But Jeremiah doesn't just casually agree to the deal.

17:16.756 --> 17:22.546
The text slows down and walks us through the entire process.

17:25.186 --> 17:26.528
He was very intentional.

17:26.748 --> 17:28.731
He weighed out the silver.

17:30.314 --> 17:31.756
He signed the deal.

17:33.018 --> 17:34.781
He sealed the documents.

17:35.361 --> 17:37.585
He called witnesses to be present.

17:38.787 --> 17:41.791
Everything is done publicly and it's done legally.

17:42.512 --> 17:45.497
In other words, Jeremiah makes the purchase official.

17:46.799 --> 17:51.205
This isn't some sort of symbolic or pretend thing.

17:51.326 --> 17:54.290
It's a real transaction, real money,

17:54.434 --> 17:57.238
real land, real legal documents.

17:58.880 --> 18:03.325
And then Jeremiah does something else that seems a little strange.

18:04.967 --> 18:13.218
He tells his scribe to take the deeds, both the sealed copy and the open copy and to place them in a clay jar.

18:14.279 --> 18:14.619
Why?

18:17.443 --> 18:19.826
He does this to the last a long time.

18:21.666 --> 18:26.612
Jeremiah is essentially creating a kind of ancient document archive.

18:28.114 --> 18:31.097
He wants these papers to be preserved.

18:33.220 --> 18:36.324
But the question is preserved for whom?

18:40.849 --> 18:45.334
Because Jeremiah himself, right, he's probably never going to see this land.

18:47.697 --> 18:49.580
He knows the exiles under way.

18:50.461 --> 18:51.602
He knows the people

18:52.002 --> 18:56.027
will be gone for decades, so why preserve the deed?

18:57.909 --> 19:12.027
The answer comes to us in verse 15, which says, for this is what the Lord of hosts, the God of Israel says, houses and fields and vineyards will again be bought in this land.

19:15.391 --> 19:16.413
That's the promise.

19:18.175 --> 19:20.818
Jeremiah buys the field because

19:21.186 --> 19:23.649
God says this is not the end of the story.

19:25.110 --> 19:26.532
This is not the end of the story.

19:27.593 --> 19:28.875
Yes, the city will fall.

19:28.955 --> 19:30.817
Yes, the people will go into exile.

19:31.538 --> 19:34.281
Yes, the land will lie desolate for a time.

19:36.123 --> 19:41.109
But one day, one day God will bring his people back.

19:42.050 --> 19:43.431
He will bring them home.

19:44.953 --> 19:49.298
And when that day comes, fields will be bought again.

19:50.626 --> 19:53.269
Homes will be built again.

19:53.329 --> 19:57.513
Vineyards will be planted again.

19:59.615 --> 20:07.442
Jeremiah's purchase is a way of saying the destruction that is coming is not the final word.

20:08.903 --> 20:11.426
The destruction that's coming is not the final word.

20:12.227 --> 20:15.610
God's promises are the final word.

20:17.211 --> 20:20.114
God's promises are the final word.

20:21.794 --> 20:28.442
Jeremiah knows that he will never walk in that field, but someone will.

20:30.905 --> 20:34.230
And that kind of hope, it has a shape to it.

20:36.012 --> 20:38.975
This is a hope that invests in God's promises.

20:41.198 --> 20:44.843
It's a hope that rehearses God's promises.

20:47.066 --> 20:50.610
And it's a hope that becomes a hopeful presence

20:51.234 --> 20:56.520
in the world, no matter how dark or bleak it may appear to be.

20:59.163 --> 21:04.329
And this is where we begin to see what hope really looks like.

21:05.610 --> 21:09.795
See, hope is not pretending the situation is better than it is.

21:12.078 --> 21:15.001
Jeremiah is an ignoring reality.

21:16.723 --> 21:19.186
So often I think we do that as believers.

21:21.602 --> 21:28.655
We cover over all of our anxieties and all of our hardships with this thin veneer of Christian sentiment.

21:31.360 --> 21:33.845
And that is dangerous to us.

21:35.087 --> 21:39.435
It is dangerous to not acknowledge reality for what it is.

21:41.038 --> 21:45.266
That has nothing more than wishful thinking and a fool's hope.

21:50.050 --> 21:58.580
Jeremiah is not naive about the fall of Jerusalem and the chaos that surrounds him.

22:00.943 --> 22:04.387
Hope in the Bible is never about the nighing reality.

22:05.949 --> 22:19.826
It's about choosing which reality will ultimately define our perspective, our wishful thinking or God's promised future.

22:23.874 --> 22:30.523
See, the king of Judah, he had plenty of wishful thinking, but it was of no value to him.

22:32.966 --> 22:40.476
He might have been sitting in the throne, but he was really locked in the prison of his own strength.

22:43.220 --> 22:50.930
And Jeremiah, while he sat in prison, was enthroned in the grace and the mercy and the hope of God.

22:56.642 --> 23:04.475
Jeremiah believes that what God has promised is more decisive than what he currently sees.

23:04.575 --> 23:09.242
And so he acts accordingly and he buys the field.

23:11.165 --> 23:14.351
Eugene Peterson puts it this way.

23:14.371 --> 23:18.818
He says, hope is buying into what we believe.

23:20.340 --> 23:23.986
Hope is buying into what we believe.

23:25.346 --> 23:30.052
Jeremiah, he's spoken many words to God's chosen people.

23:31.614 --> 23:35.218
And now he is putting his money where his mouth is.

23:36.680 --> 23:38.982
He's literally buying into the future.

23:39.163 --> 23:41.525
God has promised.

23:42.607 --> 23:45.210
From the outside, it looks absolutely foolish.

23:46.551 --> 23:47.973
It looks impractical.

23:49.415 --> 23:52.018
It looks like a terrible investment for sure.

23:53.506 --> 23:57.472
But Jeremiah is not investing in this present moment.

23:57.792 --> 24:01.598
He is investing in God's future restoration.

24:03.781 --> 24:08.989
Hope, in other words, is in investing your life in God's promise.

24:09.089 --> 24:15.218
It's choosing to live today in light of what God says will be true tomorrow.

24:16.360 --> 24:19.885
And sometimes that kind of hope, it looks strange.

24:20.246 --> 24:22.069
Sometimes it looks unreasonable.

24:22.109 --> 24:23.090
Sometimes it looks

24:23.298 --> 24:39.560
It's foolish, but it is that kind of hope that sustains the people of God through seasons when the future feels uncertain, when nothing makes sense.

24:42.283 --> 24:50.194
If hope means investing our lives in God's promises, then one of the ways we sustain hope is by returning to it

24:50.306 --> 24:57.637
Again and again and again, rehearsing God's promises over and over and over.

24:59.159 --> 25:07.011
Because when circumstances become overwhelming, our instinct is to interpret reality only through what we can see.

25:07.071 --> 25:20.210
Only through what we can see, but the people of God have always learned to interpret their circumstances through the promises of God.

25:21.410 --> 25:23.894
Jeremiah knew what God had said.

25:25.356 --> 25:33.649
He knew the exile was coming, but he also knew that God had promised restoration.

25:35.512 --> 25:40.119
And that promise shaped how he lived in the present.

25:42.763 --> 25:47.570
Remember last week we said that our faith was eschatological.

25:48.610 --> 25:58.282
And then that's just a fancy theological term that means that all of our hope is rooted in the future fulfillment of all of God's promises.

26:01.065 --> 26:09.095
All of our present hope is rooted in the future fulfillment of all of God's promises.

26:11.398 --> 26:17.906
For us, those promises are even clearer than they were for Jeremiah, right?

26:20.194 --> 26:21.055
even clearer.

26:23.358 --> 26:30.849
Because we have get to see and to look upon part of the fulfillment that he could only look forward to and hope.

26:32.170 --> 26:35.074
We know what God has done through Jesus.

26:35.094 --> 26:37.358
We just celebrated that around the Lord's table.

26:38.299 --> 26:40.502
We know that sin has been defeated.

26:41.323 --> 26:44.287
We know that death is not the final word.

26:45.869 --> 26:49.394
The New Testament keeps pointing us towards that future.

26:50.658 --> 26:54.784
Paul writes in Romans 5, 3 through 4 that suffering produces what?

26:55.144 --> 26:56.246
Perseverance.

26:57.768 --> 26:59.430
And perseverance produces what?

26:59.891 --> 27:00.592
Character.

27:00.952 --> 27:02.374
And character produces what?

27:03.676 --> 27:03.976
Hope.

27:06.800 --> 27:08.402
Suffering produces perseverance.

27:08.463 --> 27:09.624
Perseverance character.

27:09.724 --> 27:11.527
And character hope.

27:13.309 --> 27:19.698
And later in 2 Corinthians, Paul reminds us that this momentary

27:20.034 --> 27:25.079
Light affliction doesn't feel light when we're going through it.

27:25.399 --> 27:30.284
It feels like anything, but it feels so heavy.

27:30.344 --> 27:38.171
But this light and momentary affliction is producing for us what?

27:39.272 --> 27:42.636
An eternal weight of glory.

27:43.937 --> 27:49.362
An eternal weight of glory that is beyond all comparison

27:52.322 --> 27:57.608
hope grows as we rehearse those promises.

27:59.650 --> 28:21.394
As we remember what God has done through Christ, and as a reminder ourselves of what God has said, what He has said, He will do it.

28:22.818 --> 28:26.824
And Israel's fall was inevitable.

28:29.429 --> 28:31.732
God's hope is inevitable.

28:34.096 --> 28:42.329
And the future that we place, the trust that we place in the future that He promises, it is inevitable.

28:45.595 --> 28:50.162
More of our hope is not meant to stay locked away inside of our hearts.

28:51.938 --> 28:54.442
It's not something we're just supposed to keep to ourselves.

28:56.966 --> 29:00.331
It's why we gather together in person.

29:03.556 --> 29:19.922
One of my worship leading heroes is a guy named Bob Coughlin, and there's an old phrase that was coined back in the 90s by a guy named Steve Camp, and it was

29:20.226 --> 29:21.668
Worship is for an audience of one.

29:21.708 --> 29:24.071
Everyone ever hear that phrase.

29:24.091 --> 29:26.715
Worship is for an audience of one.

29:26.735 --> 29:27.897
I appreciate the sentiment.

29:27.917 --> 29:29.779
I just don't think that's biblically accurate.

29:32.343 --> 29:35.147
We have tons of evidence throughout the Psalms of corporate worship.

29:36.148 --> 29:41.595
Paul two separate times, once in Ephesians and once Colossians says that we gather together to sing to who?

29:43.118 --> 29:43.819
To each other.

29:45.481 --> 29:49.266
We sing Psalms, hymns, and spiritual songs to each other.

29:50.850 --> 29:55.836
And one of my heroes, this guy, Bob Coughlin, I like the way he puts it better.

29:55.896 --> 30:01.844
He says, worship is for God in its ends and that it's for his glory, but it's for us in its means.

30:05.609 --> 30:14.340
There's something special that happens when we gather together and we rehearse the hope of God together.

30:15.681 --> 30:19.346
As I sat in that buck row silently this morning with my head bowed,

30:19.522 --> 30:28.956
Hearing you guys singing, I was reminded of the hope of the Lord and I was encouraged and my faith was strengthened.

30:31.460 --> 30:40.714
There's something that's special that happens when we step outside of ourselves, when we do not walk our hope up inside of our hearts.

30:41.075 --> 30:48.626
It becomes visible in a way that we live among others and it becomes a hopeful

30:48.834 --> 30:51.838
presence.

30:51.858 --> 30:53.921
And we see this in the life of Jeremiah, right?

30:53.961 --> 30:55.523
The city is under siege.

30:57.846 --> 30:59.067
Fear would have been everywhere.

30:59.408 --> 31:00.970
The future was uncertain.

31:02.011 --> 31:04.234
And then Jeremiah buys a field.

31:05.616 --> 31:07.258
People would have noticed this.

31:09.721 --> 31:13.826
They would have asked, why would anyone do that?

31:15.008 --> 31:16.690
Why would anyone do that?

31:18.242 --> 31:23.731
His action became a quiet, but powerful witness.

31:23.811 --> 31:29.139
It was a way of saying, God is not finished with His people.

31:29.159 --> 31:31.062
God is not finished with His people.

31:32.665 --> 31:46.386
In a world that often feels anxious and uncertain, the church is called to live that same way, to invest

31:47.330 --> 31:50.254
where investment seems unlikely to bring a return.

31:53.159 --> 32:07.860
We're called to live with the same sort of hope, not with a naive optimism, not by denying reality, but with a steady confidence that God is still at work.

32:09.903 --> 32:17.074
Sometimes the most powerful witness we offer is simply living with hope.

32:17.890 --> 32:20.333
when others are losing theirs.

32:20.814 --> 32:23.298
It is not all about us.

32:25.561 --> 32:27.744
It is not all about me.

32:36.536 --> 32:46.290
Living with hope when others are losing theirs is an incredible gift.

32:46.690 --> 32:50.394
that the Lord bestows upon us for the sake of someone else.

32:53.098 --> 33:03.931
So this is a hope that invests, a hope that rehearses, and a hope that is lived out in community.

33:06.954 --> 33:10.098
All this kind of begs the question,

33:13.218 --> 33:19.947
All begs the question, what field is the Lord calling you to buy this morning?

33:22.430 --> 33:31.783
How might he be calling you to invest your life?

33:31.803 --> 33:39.954
One of my favorite theologians, he puts it this way, he says, the most powerful work of God

33:41.282 --> 34:01.344
The gathering of people out of Satan's clutches into Christ's kingdom comes not through warfare or politics, not through the influence of money or fame, but through the folly of what we preach.

34:05.148 --> 34:10.354
The folly that was preached to Jeremiah was by a field that is under siege

34:11.234 --> 34:22.673
It is being trampled across by enemy combatants overrun by the field in hope because I am giving you a promise.

34:25.037 --> 34:29.324
What field is the Lord calling you to buy this morning?

34:31.768 --> 34:37.938
What folly is he calling you to buy into this morning?

34:40.674 --> 34:46.981
What fool's hope is he calling you to take up this morning?

34:54.409 --> 34:55.871
His promises are sure.

34:58.294 --> 34:59.395
They are inevitable.

35:02.779 --> 35:06.343
And we can plant our hope firmly on them this morning.

35:06.943 --> 35:07.284
Amen?

35:08.625 --> 35:09.266
Just pray with me.

35:15.650 --> 35:20.735
Jesus, you are the greatest fulfilled promise ever.

35:23.678 --> 35:27.121
And you are the promise that keeps on giving.

35:31.145 --> 35:39.112
You were the promised Messiah who came to rescue and to save the lost.

35:41.054 --> 35:44.978
And you were the promised Messiah who will come again

35:46.882 --> 36:07.451
who will declare his reign over all of the created order, who will make all things right, who will separate the sheep from the goats, and who will wipe away the tear of every one of his precious sheep's eyes.

36:09.894 --> 36:15.602
And so Lord, we rest in that hope this morning and we live in the reality of it this morning.

36:16.418 --> 36:23.347
And we pray for strength, we pray for confidence to take up that hope.

36:27.133 --> 36:32.941
To take up that hope and to follow after you all of our days.

36:36.585 --> 36:45.778
Bless us with that confidence this morning and the reality that you will fulfill your promises.

36:47.714 --> 36:54.561
We entrust our lives and we entrust our church to you this morning to you this.

36:54.581 --> 36:54.841
Amen.

36:59.006 --> 37:03.430
Thank you so much for listening to the Crossway Christian Church sermon podcast.

37:04.031 --> 37:14.802
We're so glad you could join us and if you'd like to plug into the life of our community or have any questions that we might be able to answer, visit our website crosswaycc.org to connect with us.

37:15.170 --> 37:17.150
Until the next time, we can be with you.

37:17.211 --> 37:19.090
May the Lord bless you and keep you.

